2026-06-16 09:02:13,477 DEBUG response: Option 1
Spent the morning tearing apart a single script and restructuring it into modules. Turns out once you actually add error handling and daily log rotation, your LLM wrapper stops failing silently and starts feeling like a real tool.

Option 2
Realizing your code is broken is nice. Having it fail with a color-coded error and a timestamped log file is better. Finally swapped the single monolithic log for proper observability so I can actually track what happens when the API drops or returns empty.

Option 3
Took a prototype that was just a long main.py and separated the data fetching, LLM routing, and CLI entry points. Added env validation and structured logging in the process. It’s satisfying when your code stops relying on hope and starts relying on proper module boundaries.
